2026-04-21 01:40:07 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['lamp module internal wiring between diode output node and main lamp positive terminal', 'main lamp negative (return) connection in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the load module input stays at ~11.8–11.9 V during the 0.5 s outages, so the supply and control modules are stable. At those times the main lamp still has about 11.0 V across it and 0.77 V appears across the series diode, indicating normal forward conduction and no loss of drive from upstream.\n\nThe indicator lamp in parallel with the main lamp was visually confirmed to stay lit steadily and its terminal voltages (about 11.06 V at its positive side, ~0.05 V at its negative side) remain essentially unchanged. This proves that the diode output node and return path in the load module remain continuously energized and that the parallel branch feeding the indicator lamp is healthy.\n\nYet the main lamp intermittently goes dark while the indicator lamp (on the same diode output node) remains bright. The main lamp itself has already been replaced and found not faulty. Therefore the only remaining explanation is an intermittent open or very high resistance in the wiring specific to the main lamp branch: either the connection from the diode/indicator junction to the main lamp positive terminal, or the main lamp’s own negative/return connection back to the common node. Vibrations, thermal expansion, or contact oxidation could create a periodic open resulting in the observed brief dropouts.\n\nThus the fault is localized to the main-lamp-specific wiring/contacts inside the load module, not to the lamp filament, diode, indicator lamp, or upstream modules.'
