2026-04-21 01:40:37 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module series protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show that:\n- The power‑supply voltage is rock steady.\n- The control module output and relay remain stable and fully ON; no 20‑s variation is seen in the control path.\n- The load‑module input stays at ~11.8–11.9 V during the 0.5 s outages.\n- During an outage the main lamp still has ~11.0 V across it while the series diode drops ~0.77 V, exactly as when the lamp is lit.\n- The internal indicator lamp in parallel with the main lamp remains stably lit and at full voltage.\n- The main lamp itself is healthy (120 Ω, no intermittent opens) and its wiring has been checked and found OK.\n\nThis means the *only* element whose behaviour is consistent with an intermittent, load‑dependent series resistance that reduces the current enough for the main lamp to extinguish (while still allowing the much smaller indicator lamp to appear normal) is the series protection diode in the load module. A partially damaged diode can intermittently enter a high‑resistance or quasi‑open state under load, yet still show a near‑normal forward drop when measured, especially with limited bandwidth measurements and a parallel lamp maintaining voltage.\n\nSince all other modules and wiring have been effectively excluded by measurement or prior repair attempts, the most probable root cause is an intermittent internal fault in the load‑module series protection diode. I recommend replacing that diode (or its small PCB assembly) in the load module.'
