2026-04-21 01:40:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module internal indicator lamp', 'load module indicator lamp parallel connection across main lamp (wiring or PCB traces)'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply‑side elements are stable: the PSU output, control‑module output, relay contacts, cabling, and series protection diode all remain at steady voltage during the 0.5 s, 20 s‑period outages. The main lamp always has about 11 V across it, even when it goes dark, and its filament tests good and behaves normally when powered directly. The only component that is electrically in parallel with the main lamp is the small indicator lamp inside the load module.\n\nThe measurements on the indicator show ~11.06 V at its positive terminal and ~0.05 V at its negative terminal, i.e. essentially the full supply, continuously, with no reported oscillation in step with the main‑lamp outages. That implies the indicator branch is continuously drawing current, while the main lamp periodically ceases to conduct despite a correct supply across it.\n\nGiven that the main lamp, its wiring, and the protection diode have been explicitly ruled out as faulty, the most plausible remaining explanation is a fault local to the indicator branch that intermittently diverts or starves current from the main lamp only, for example:\n- an internal short or partial short within the indicator bulb structure that periodically changes resistance with self‑heating, or\n- a wiring/PCB fault on the indicator branch (e.g., unintended series resistance, whisker, or localized overheating) that modulates the current sharing between the parallel paths.\n\nBecause the indicator is in parallel with the main lamp at the diode output node, an abnormal, time‑varying resistance or intermittent short in this branch can cause the main lamp current to collapse for a brief interval while the indicator itself remains visibly lit (its small filament may tolerate the transient without visible flicker). Replacing or repairing the indicator lamp and its immediate parallel connection should therefore clear the periodic 0.5 s outages while leaving the rest of the system unchanged.'
