2026-04-21 01:42:03 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal indicator LED ‘switched cables indicator’ and its series resistor network / wiring (i.e., the circuit that should be in parallel with the load path)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical tests show a perfectly steady 12 V supply from the PSU through the control module to the load module, with about 11 V across the main lamp and roughly 0.11–0.114 A of current during the intervals when the main lamp is reported to go dark. The protection diode drops a normal ~0.77 V. The internal indicator lamp in the load module, which is hard‑wired in parallel with the main lamp, also sees ~11 V and remains steadily lit. Continuity of all external cabling, the protection diode, and the lamp wiring has been verified, and replacing the main lamp, its wiring, the protection diode, and the load‑module indicator lamp produced no change. The relay stays closed and its output voltage is steady, and control‑module sensor/driver nodes show no 20 s oscillation. Therefore the only element that is intended to show a 20 s / 0.5 s ‘switched’ indication but has not yet been conclusively verified electrically is the control‑module ‘switched cables indicator’ LED and its series resistor network.\n\nIf this indicator LED (or its resistor/wiring) were miswired so that it intermittently shunts or partially loads the lamp circuit every 20 s (for example due to an internal intermittent short or incorrect PCB trace that momentarily diverts current or modulates the local reference at the load connection), the control‑module output voltage readings—taken at low impedance measurement points—could remain essentially constant while the instantaneous luminous output of the main lamp drops, even though the average measured current over the sampling interval appears unchanged. This is consistent with the simulator note that the timing network is oscillating while the relay itself stays closed: the only place that oscillation could couple into the load is via the indicator LED path that is associated with the switched cables. Since all other plausible components and configuration errors have been eliminated by direct replacement or measurement, the remaining consistent root cause is a fault in the control‑module output indicator LED circuit (LED, its resistor, or its PCB traces/wiring) that interacts with the oscillating timing node to produce the observed visual 0.5 s / 20 s lamp darkening while pass DC measurements remain nominal.'
