2026-04-21 01:42:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main external lamp physical/optical implementation in the load module (i.e., the part that emits light to the outside, distinct from the electrically modeled filament and indicator lamp)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a completely stable system: the battery output is steady; the control‑module output and relay are steady; the load‑module series diode conducts normally; the main lamp filament has correct resistance; during the apparent 0.5 s “off” intervals, the lamp still has ~11 V across it and ~0.114 A flowing, identical to normal ON conditions. The indicator lamp in parallel is also steadily lit at full voltage. Therefore, from the circuit’s point of view, the main lamp is continuously energized with constant power and no intermittency.\n\nThe only remaining way to reconcile the symptom “lamp turns off for 0.5 s every 20 s” with this data is that the *optical* component that sends light to the outside is faulty or mis‑implemented, while the electrical filament element is fine. In other words, the part of the load module that should expose the main lamp’s light to the observer is not faithfully representing the energized state. This might correspond, in the actual hardware, to the wrong LED or bulb being used as the ‘main’ external lamp, an internal mechanical/optical shutter driven by some periodic mechanism, or (in a simulation environment) a mismatch between the modeled electrical lamp element and the UI element designated as the “main lamp” indicator.\n\nHence the root cause is that the external main‑lamp optical implementation in the load module is incorrect, even though all associated electrical components (filament, wiring, diode, parallel indicator) are healthy. Repair would consist of correcting/replacing this optical/indicator implementation so that it continuously displays light whenever the lamp filament node is energized.'
