2026-04-21 01:42:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal ground / negative reference connection between control module and load module (shared return path wiring, plugs, or PCB trace)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show that during the supposed 0.5 s “off” intervals the main lamp still has ~11 V across its own terminals and draws the normal ~0.114 A, identical to normal operation. The power‑supply module output is rock‑steady, the relay is continuously closed, the control‑module output rails stay at ~11.85 V and 0 V with no oscillation, the series diode is fine, the lamp filament and its local wiring in the load module are sound, and the parallel indicator lamp in the load module also remains steadily lit at ~11 V.\n\nTherefore the load branch itself is behaving perfectly: there is no real interruption of lamp power. Yet the fault description insists that the external lamp appears to darken every 20 s. Given the simulator constraints, the only remaining element that can reconcile ‘normal electrical behaviour everywhere in the load branch’ with ‘perceived periodic outage’ is an intermittent or shared‑impedance issue in the common negative / ground reference between modules.\n\nIf the control module’s local ground (used as reference for some measurements and potentially for the observer’s viewpoint) is intermittently shifting relative to the load module’s true return, the voltages measured within the control module and at its outputs can remain nominal, while the effective reference seen by the external observation point or by other parts of the system moves. This can create apparent changes in lamp brightness or state without altering the locally measured 11 V across the lamp or the current in its positive lead. Such a fault would reside in the shared return path wiring or PCB trace that ties the control‑module negative terminal to the load‑module negative terminal.\n\nThus the most consistent root cause is a faulty or high‑impedance common negative reference between the control module and the load module (e.g., cracked solder joint, damaged trace, or marginal connector on the return line), which has not yet been directly repaired/replaced in previous steps that focused on the positive lead, the diode, or the lamps themselves.'
