2026-04-21 01:43:26 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contact wiring relative to switched‑cables indicator LED (miswired so load path bypasses relay contacts and is permanently connected to supply)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show that: (1) the battery supply is rock‑steady; (2) the control‑module output is a steady ~11.85 V with no 20 s / 0.5 s fluctuation; (3) the relay coil drive is steady and both relay coil terminals sit at ~11.85 V, confirming the relay is continuously energized and its contacts remain closed mechanically; (4) the load‑module input voltage, series diode drop, main lamp terminal voltages, and current all remain essentially constant (~11 V across a 120 Ω lamp with ~0.11 A) during the periods when the user observes the lamp as ‘off’. Electrically, the lamp and its parallel indicator are continuously powered without interruption.\n\nWe have already ruled out faults in the main lamp, the load‑module wiring, the protection diode, the indicator lamp, cable polarity, PSU, ambient‑sensor node, and ground/return connections. The only remaining plausible explanation that fits all electrical data and previous wrong hypotheses is a configuration/assembly error inside the control module: the relay’s switched contacts are not actually in series with the outgoing load path. Instead, the load cables are effectively wired directly to the unswitched 12 V supply (or to the wrong side of the relay), and the ‘switched cables indicator’ LED network is wired across the nominal contact node in a way that does not influence the load. As a result, the relay and its timing circuit may oscillate internally every 20 s, but because the load is never actually routed through the contacts, the lamp remains electrically steady. The apparent 0.5 s outages must therefore arise solely from this miswiring: the system is not implementing the intended switching function, and the load path bypasses the relay.\n\nThus the root cause is a wiring/configuration fault in the control module relay contact path relative to the load output and the switched‑cables indicator LED, not in any of the discrete components that have been individually tested or replaced.'
