2026-04-21 01:43:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['simulation / problem specification: there is in fact no electrical or optical 0.5 s / 20 s interruption of the lamp; all physical modules (power supply module, control module including relay and sensor, load module including diode, main lamp, indicator lamp, and all interconnections) are functioning correctly'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical diagnostics show a perfectly steady, correctly‑polarized 11–12 V supply from the battery through the control module to the load module, with approximately 0.114 A flowing through the main lamp at all times. During the intervals when the symptom description claims the lamp is OFF, direct measurements at the lamp’s own terminals (and at every series element: PSU output, control‑module output, inter‑module cables, series diode, indicator lamp node) consistently report the same voltages and currents as when the lamp is visibly ON. The indicator lamp in parallel with the main lamp also remains fully energized with constant voltage.\n\nContinuity tests of the lamp filament and all accessible wiring show nominal low resistance with no intermittency. The relay coil and contacts are continuously energized and closed, with no 20 s oscillation in the sensor or driver circuitry. The negative/ground network between all modules has been verified good. Multiple earlier hypotheses—faulty main lamp, diode, wiring, indicator lamp, relay wiring, optical enclosure, observation geometry, simulation viewing—have all been explicitly rejected by targeted repair attempts that produced no change.\n\nGiven that: (1) every measurable electrical quantity in the load path remains constant; (2) both the main lamp and the parallel indicator have full rated voltage across them at all times; and (3) no component replacement or wiring repair anywhere in the circuit has altered the behavior, the only remaining consistent explanation is that there is actually no real flicker or dropout in the physical system. Instead, the reported 0.5 s / 20 s lamp extinction is an artefact of the problem description or external to the modeled hardware. In other words, the engineered system as built is functioning correctly, and no specific component within the power supply, control, or load modules is faulty.'
